# Windows development environment

This project is developed on **Windows**. Use **PowerShell 7** (`pwsh`) for all shell commands — not bash, not cmd, not Windows PowerShell 5.1.

## Command chaining

PowerShell 7 supports `&&`, `||`, and `;`:

```powershell
cd "c:\Users\ibroh\Project\pathprofiler" && .\gradlew :composeApp:test
```

Use `&&` when the next command should run only if the previous one succeeded. Use `;` for unconditional chaining. Do not use bash-only syntax (`export`, bash-style `$(...)` subshells, HEREDOC `cat << 'EOF'`/`EOF`).
Do not use Unix tools that don't exist in PowerShell. Never pipe to `head`, `tail`, `sed`, or `awk`. Use `Select-Object -First N` / `-Last N` instead of `head`/`tail`, use the Read/StrReplace/Write tools instead of `sed`/`awk` for file editing, and use `rg` (ripgrep) instead of `grep`.

## Go toolchain

The Go toolchain is installed at `C:\Program Files\go\bin`.

- When running Go commands (e.g., `go build`, `go test`, `go mod tidy`, etc.), ensure `C:\Program Files\go\bin` is in the PATH, or invoke the Go binary directly via its full path.
- Example: `& "C:\Program Files\go\bin\go.exe" build .`

Use Windows path separators (`\`) and PowerShell syntax (`$env:VAR`, not `export VAR=`).
